Buffalo Bob &quot;Old Man&quot;,<br><br>
The last sentence says it all.<br><br>
I think that &quot;hope (does) springs eternal&quot; and am looking forward to the future.<br><br>
I have had the good fortune to meet 3 Vietnam Veterans in person whom I would never have met had it not been for the Internet. As Cook explains about his Marine reunions, these meetings have brought forth much in the way of support and encouragement. We even have read, out loud, stories we have written - something we would never have done 25 years ago. I had the pleasure of a late night phone chat with a certain haypitcher from OK a few weeks ago that did me alot of good.<br><br>
This POV forum *is* sacred in that it brings us together, and whatever happened in 1970 or 1969 or 1971 should not be allowed to affect the future and what it will bring to those who served. That is: the admiration and respect, that you speak of, for those who served their country. Period.<br><br>
I realize that there is still much bitterness about the war, and that we can go on forever and a day arguing. But the important thing to realize and to remember every day is that the best days are coming for those who served in Vietnam.
<p><code>-- wingman#greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


